simplify core: get rid of watcher/watcher_ref split all watchers now behave like they did in 0.13: the incref themselves while in use by the event loop (that is, _ref versions are kept but without _ref in the name)one reason for that is that doing ev_watcher_stop in watcher's __dealloc__ crashes: loop attribute is no longer a valid reference in __dealloc__; (although this could probably be worked around)nnanother reason is to make it simpler, having 2 sets of watchers is complex to explain.nnthird reason is: using watchers that automatically stopped themselves on __dealloc__ introduced a lotnof incompatibilities and potentially unexpected behaviour compared to gevent-0.13. it is also not recommended in general to depend on CPython's refcounting for resource management.n

core: make io class similar to all other watchers, use the same callback function for all watchers; make loop and watcher classes public- the way io calls its callback is changed: it used to pass (events, self) always, now it passes *args like the other watchers do.n  in order to find out which events fired, start the watcher as watcher.start(func, EVENTS, *args) - func will be called as func(<EVENTS FIRED>, args)n- do a type check that callback passed to start() or to watcher.callback.__set__ is a callable;n- same for 'args' attribute, except allow it to be Nonen- declare some of the methods as cpdef for speed when used in C coden- make '_incref' readonly rather than publicn- add cdef methods _start() and _feed() because start() and feed() use *args and cannot be cpdefn- update modules affect by API change: gevent.select and gevent.servern

Semaphore: avoid copying list of links; rawlink() no longer schedules notificationAvoid copying list of links by maintaining a 'dirty' flag that causesn_notify_links to restart iteration. This makes sure that we don't missna recently added link because notification is already in progress.nnIt is possible to notify the same links (that did not remove themselvers)nmore than once, but it's better than not notifying some links at all.nnrawlink() no longer schedules notification immediatelly if needed, becausenthere seem to be utility in such behaviour.n

resolver_ares: improve getaddrinfoFor string ports (e.g. http) resolver_ares/getaddrinfo previously onlynconsulted getservbyname(port, tcp) or getservbyname(port, udp), but never both.nnIt seems that checking of both work (and creating result based on that) makes fornbetter compatibility with stock getaddrinfo, at least on linux.n

resolver_ares: fallback to threadpoolFor non-network requests, like localhost, it seems to be quite hardnto make gevent.ares to do the right (=compatible with stdlib) thing.nnSo we check if host does not have '.' and if that's the case,nwe fallback to using threadpool.nnThis covers requests like localhost, ip6-localhost and Python-specificnthings, like <broadcast>nnIt's possible to disable this by passing use_threadpool=False to ResolverAresnor by settings resolver.pool = None.n

many fixes for the testsuite; rewrite testrunnerThe stdlib tests are now included in the repository. since ubuntundoes not ships them in any package.nnThe testrunner is completely rewritten. When testrunner.py was originally writtenna lot of tests were failing and some of them were hanging. Thus testrunner.pynwas focused on proving good reports and could retry the tests with a particularntest case disabled if it detected time out. Now testrunner is somewhat simpler asnwe mostly concerned whether the tests pass or not. It also runs the testsnconcurrently, to improve the speed at which we get the results back from travis-ci.nSome tests time execution and assert certain timings, this can fail, especially whennthe number of workers is bigger than cpu count. The new testrunner will re-tryntests that failed in a sequential run, when nothing else is run. If this fixesnthe problem, the test is reported as succeeded, but only on the second try and doesnreports the whole suite as failed.nn.travis.yml is fixed to download binary packages for all dependencies and use system python.nnrename test__benchmarks.py to xtest__benchmarks.py to exclude it form testrunner.py.nnExclude test__count from test_thread.py, because it uses function thread._count() we don't implementnnRun monkey patched tests twice, first with patch_all(), then with patch_all(Event=True)n

BaseServer and its derived class StreamServer was relying on CPython's reference counting behaviour to close the socket (or other arguments) when the handler finished. This breaks under PyPy which uses a different GC.Fix it by wrapping the handler and explicitly closing the socket when it returns. This fixes test__servernunder PyPy, although not in a particularly elegant way. It also negates the need for 57936127c2cdafcf04039a371903810bf96e5bd6.n

subprocess.Popen `bufsize` option actually usedThe `bufsize` option of the subprocess.Popen module wasn't used (atnall), meaning that the default was usually buffered (platformndependant), and was also not modifiable.nnThis was also different from the behavior of the vanillansubprocess.Popen modulennNote that this change the default behavior of the class (bufferednbecomes unbuffered in most cases)n

Make DummySemaphore.acquire return TrueUsually gevent.lock.DummySemaphore and gevent.lock.Semaphore are used interchangeablynand since gevent.lock.Semaphore.acquire return a boolean for checking if acquiringnlock failed or worked, it will make sense to just return True for DummySemaphore.acquire,nthis way we can just use afterward ``if not acquired: ...``.n

Port Python 2.7.9 ssl.pyResolves #477.nnIn Python 2.7.9, we have new SSL interfaces, that are not quitenthe old Python 2 interfaces, nor the same as the Python 3 interfaces.nnThis creates a new SSL module, _sslgte279.py, for Python 2 versionsngreater than or equal 2.7.9, ported from Python 2.7.9's ssl.py:nhttps://hg.python.org/cpython/file/648dcafa7e5f/Lib/ssl.py.nnThe process of porting was done by starting with gevent's ssl3.py andnbackporting Python 2.7.9's ssl.py.nnFixes these tests under Python 2.7.9:nn - /usr/local/bin/python -u -m monkey_test --Event test_urllib2net.pyn - /usr/local/bin/python -u -m monkey_test test_urllib2net.pyn - /usr/local/bin/python -u test__ssl.pynnNo new test failures. Still failing since 72119c8:nn - /usr/local/bin/python -u -m monkey_test --Event test_ssl.pyn - /usr/local/bin/python -u -m monkey_test test_ssl.pyn - /usr/local/bin/python -u test__pywsgi.pyn - /usr/local/bin/python -u test__makefile_ref.pyn - /usr/local/bin/python -u test__socket.pyn - /usr/local/bin/python -u test___example_servers.pyn - /usr/local/bin/python -u -m monkey_test --Event test_ftplib.pyn - /usr/local/bin/python -u test__socket_ssl.pyn - /usr/local/bin/python -u -m monkey_test test_ftplib.pyn - /usr/local/bin/python -u test__all__.pynnIn addition, basic HTTPS requests were tested with urllib3==1.10.2nand requests==2.6.0.n

Improve compliance of select.select and select.poll- Compliance: If :func:`gevent.select.select` is given a negative *timeout*n  argument, raise an exception like the standard library does.n- Compliance: If :func:`gevent.select.select` is given closed or invalidn  file descriptors in any of its lists, raise the appropriaten  ``EBADF`` exception like the standard library does. Previously,n  libev would tend to return the descriptor as ready. In the worstn  case, this adds an extra system call, but may also reduce latency ifn  descriptors are ready at the time of entry.n- Compliance: :meth:`gevent.select.poll.unregister` raises an exception if *fd* is notn  registered, like the standard library.n- Compliance: :meth:`gevent.select.poll.poll` returns an event withn  ``POLLNVAL`` for registered fds that are invalid. Previously itn  would tend to report both read and write events.n

Use subclass of dict for WSGI environ.Right now, this is only used for suppressing the printing of potentiallynsensitive information, but in the future there could be other uses.nnThis is technically not compliant with PEP3333 which specifies that thentype(environ) must be dict, but it's not clear if that practicallynmatters anymore (it looks like it might be a holdover from supportingnPython 1.5.2 before one could subclass the builtin dict; see https://mail.python.org/pipermail/web-sig/2003-December/000394.html).nnFixes #779.n

Attempt and FAIL to implement fork/child on libuv.Sadly, libuv simply cannot be used in a child process that has fork()'dnfrom a parent that also used libuv. The result is a pretty quick abort()nand crash.nnIt *may* be possible to implement `subprocess` on top of uv_spawn (Inhaven't looked into that), but things like multiprocessing andnfutures.ProcessPoolExecutor would be completely broken.nnComments in commit.n

Fix destroying the loop and properly close handles.Sadly this exposes the fact that libuv doesn't allow multiple handlesnfor a given poll fd. Nor does it raise clear errors until you try tonclose them in an order different from the inverse of the one they werencreated in. Doing so simply aborts the process when libuv realises thatnthe watcher it has registered is not the watcher you're closing.nnThis further means that multiple watchers wont' get the right set ofnevents delivered, I think (though most of the tests were passing until Indiscovered this crash).n

monkey: exec scripts in global scopeCommit 59581a8a3b7b0a4722fb3f7074fce6cd4c700bfd Add python 3.5nselectors test, and remove the devpoll selector under 3.5. also updatenthe monkey documentation. Introduced a regression by moving the exec ofnscripts into a main() function. If the script being run with exec hasnimport statements those are now locally scoped to the main() functionnwhich can break the script.nnIt does not appear that this local scoping was intentional so the fix isnto exec the script in the global scope, returning the previous behavior.nThis also requires setting __package__ = None otherwise the scriptnappears to be run in the gevent __package__n

Defer adjusting the stdlib's list of active threads until ``threading`` is monkey patched.Previously this was done when :mod:`gevent.threading` was imported.nThat module is documented to be used as a helper for monkey patching,nso this should generally functionally be the same, but somenapplications ignore the directly import that module anyway.nnA positive consequence is that ``import gevent.threading, threading;nthreading.current_thread()`` will no longer return a DummyThreadnbefore monkey-patching. Another positive consequence is that PyPy willnno longer print a ``KeyError`` on exit if :mod:`gevent.threading` wasnimported *without* monkey-patching.nnFixes #984.n

Attempt to fix (or workaround) test__socket.py on Windows.It runs locally for me on Win10/Py3.6 with both libev and libuv.nnIt had been sometimes failing since 2016-02 for 2.7 and 2016-04 forn3.5.nnHere's the comment in the code indicating what I tracked down. Notenthat the changes are more of a workaround than a true fix:nnXXX: On Windows (at least with libev), if we have a cleanup/tearDownnmethod that does 'del self.listener' AND we haven't sometimenpreviously closed the listener (while the test body was executing) wentend to sometimes see hangs when tests run in succession; notablyntest_empty_send followed by test_makefile produces a hang inntest_makefile when it tries to read from the client_file, because thenaccept() call in accept_once has not yet returned a new socket tonwrite to.nnThe cause *seems* to be that the listener socket in both tests getsnthe same fileno(); or, at least, if we don't del the listener object,nwe get a different fileno, and that scenario works.nnPerhaps our logic is wrong in libev_vfd in the way we usen_open_osfhandle and determine we can close it?nnAdditional note:nnPossibly libuv doesn't suffer from this since it takes the SOCKETnobject directly? I didn't fully test that situation, but libuv testsnwere failing and are now passing.n

Fix an occasional crash in monkey patched 3.6/test_socket.pyFirst the crash report:nn```n  testInterruptedRecvmsgTimeout (__main__.InterruptedRecvTimeoutTest) ... Traceback (most recent call last):nFile /home/travis/build/gevent/gevent/src/gevent/_ffi/loop.py, line 83, in python_callbackn  def python_callback(self, handle, revents):nFile /home/travis/build/gevent/gevent/src/greentest/3.6/test_socket.py, line 3698, in <lambda>n  lambda signum, frame: 1 / 0)n  ZeroDivisionError: division by zeron  Fri Dec 15 16:09:36 2017n  okn  testInterruptedSendTimeout (__main__.InterruptedSendTimeoutTest) ... Fatal Python error: ffi.from_handle() detected that the address passed points to garbage. If it is really the result of ffi.new_handle(), then the Python object has already been garbage collectednn  Thread 0x00002b26d4c01700 (most recent call first):nFile /home/travis/build/gevent/gevent/src/gevent/_threading.py, line 152 in waitnFile /home/travis/build/gevent/gevent/src/gevent/_threading.py, line 436 in getnFile /home/travis/build/gevent/gevent/src/gevent/threadpool.py, line 200 in _workernn  Thread 0x00002b26d4a00700 (most recent call first):nFile /home/travis/build/gevent/gevent/src/gevent/_threading.py, line 152 in waitnFile /home/travis/build/gevent/gevent/src/gevent/_threading.py, line 436 in getnFile /home/travis/build/gevent/gevent/src/gevent/threadpool.py, line 200 in _workernn  Current thread 0x00002b26cc7b2a00 (most recent call first):nFile /home/travis/build/gevent/gevent/src/gevent/_ffi/loop.py, line 178 in python_stopnFile /home/travis/build/gevent/gevent/src/gevent/libuv/loop.py, line 289 in runnFile /home/travis/build/gevent/gevent/src/gevent/hub.py, line 688 in runn```nnThe main problem turned out to be the way in which libuv reportsnsignals at random times, much worse than the way libev does. This lednto callback functions unexpectedly returning 0, because that's thendefault for an unhandled exception or an onerror handler that returnsnNone. That in turn led to calls to python_stop that we weren'tnexpecting using a handle that had already been deallocated.nnThe fix is to both be defensive about what handles we try to use, andnto be more explicit about our error returns.n

Centralize configuration in a ``gevent.config`` object.This lets us document things more clearly, and, with care, allowsnconfiguring gevent from Python code without any environment varibles.nnAll the fileobject implementations needed to be moved out of then``gevent.fileobject`` module so as not to introduce import cycles thatnmade configuring from code impossible.nnFixes #1090n

The gevent.select.poll object must keep a tighter handle on the lifetime of io watchers it spawns. Previously they were leaking if not unregistered, which some callers fail to do --- looking at you, dnspython.

Fix test__core_timer.py by not destroying the default loop. D'oh!Before I realized that was the root cause, I refactored to avoidnstarting the hub greenlet *at all*, and that also fixed the problem.nnThe problem was that some versions of CPython using the libev-cextnloop (and only that one) would crash garbage collecting angreenlet (presumably the hub greenlet, which was attached to andestroyed loop):nn0   libsystem_kernel.dylibt0x00007fff66455e3e __pthread_kill + 10n1   libsystem_pthread.dylib   t0x00007fff66594150 pthread_kill + 333n2   libsystem_c.dylib t0x00007fff663648fe raise + 26n3   libsystem_platform.dylib  t0x00007fff66587f5a _sigtramp + 26n4   ???   t000000000000000000 0 + 0n5   greenlet.cpython-35m-darwin.sot0x000000010d76b297 green_clear + 183n6   org.python.python t0x000000010c707e0c collect + 1824n7   org.python.python t0x000000010c7076e3 _PyGC_CollectNoFail + 43n8   org.python.python t0x000000010c6e81d4 PyImport_Cleanup + 968n9   org.python.python t0x000000010c6f1b49 Py_Finalize + 92n10  org.python.python t0x000000010c6f20d5 Py_Exit + 13n11  org.python.python t0x000000010c6f4631 handle_system_exit + 320n12  org.python.python t0x000000010c6f42a1 PyErr_PrintEx + 42nnWe should take a look at that and see if we can do something more graceful.n

Introduce GEVENT_TRACK_GREENLET_TREE to disable greenlet tree featuresAs a performance optimization for applications where spawningngreenlets is critical. Plus some other optimizations to speed upnspawning in the general case.nnCPython 3.6 with 1.2.2 vs these changes with tracking disabled:nn| Benchmark  | 36_122_bench_spawn | 36config_bench_spawn_tree_off |n+------------------------+--------------------+-------------------------------+n| eventlet spawn | 12.6 us| 12.2 us: 1.04x faster (-4%)   |n| eventlet sleep | 5.22 us| 4.97 us: 1.05x faster (-5%)   |n| gevent spawn   | 4.27 us| 5.06 us: 1.19x slower (+19%)  |n| gevent sleep   | 2.63 us| 1.25 us: 2.11x faster (-53%)  |n| geventpool spawn   | 9.00 us| 8.31 us: 1.08x faster (-8%)   |n| geventpool sleep   | 4.82 us| 2.83 us: 1.70x faster (-41%)  |n| geventraw spawn| 2.51 us| 2.81 us: 1.12x slower (+12%)  |n| geventraw sleep| 649 ns | 679 ns: 1.05x slower (+5%)|n| geventpool join| 3.47 us| 1.42 us: 2.44x faster (-59%)  |n| geventpool spawn kwarg | 11.0 us| 8.95 us: 1.23x faster (-19%)  |n| geventraw spawn kwarg  | 3.87 us| 4.20 us: 1.08x slower (+8%)   |nnThe differences compared to master are hard to quantify because thenstandard deviation ends up being more than 10% of the mean in manyncases---and about a 10% improvement is what we typically see, so itngoes back and forth.n

Make more performance-sensitive places use _get_hub_noargs, since under Python 3 it is twice as fast to call as get_hub.

Add support for a background monitoring thread to be associated with each hub.Right now, it is used to detect blocked event loops, and it is extensible by users. In the future there will be some more default monitoring options (e.g., memory).nnRefs #1021.n
The extra threads that only eventually die mean we need to skip the leakcheck.

More careful handling of threadpool threads that have a hub.The threadpolo worker greenlet itself is meant to spend much of its time blocking, so don't report on it if it does.nnOnly if we switch greenlets while running the user's code should we start looking for blocking.n
Killing the monitoring thread should restore the greenlet trace function.

Move PeriodicMonitoringThread to its own file.And give it unittest coverage. (Using it as an actual thread didn'tnproduce coverage metrics because we use 'greenlet' concurrency.)nnAdd a rudimentary scheduler so that functions that don't want to runnas often as the minimum stay (very roughly) on their period.n

Start having the monitor thread emit events for monitored conditions.This is the only reasonable path I could think of to enable memory monitoring, with gevent just being responsible for monitoring the memory and detecting overage conditions, while users plug in their own policies.n

Add benchmark for using subprocess.Popen to create /usr/bin/true [skip ci]In response to #1172nnThe following numbers are for my machine on macOS 10.13.3 with MAXFDnof 50000.nnPython 2.7:nn.....................nspawn native no close_fds: Mean +- std dev: 1.81 ms +- 0.04 msn.....................nspawn gevent no close_fds: Mean +- std dev: 2.11 ms +- 0.08 msn.....................nspawn native close_fds: Mean +- std dev: 31.0 ms +- 0.7 msn.....................nspawn gevent close_fds: Mean +- std dev: 31.6 ms +- 0.6 msnnNotice that the times when close_fd=True (not the default on 2.7) arenabout the same. 2.7 uses the same Python loop we do to close all thenfds.nnNow 3.7:nn.....................nspawn native no close_fds: Mean +- std dev: 1.34 ms +- 0.04 msn.....................nspawn gevent no close_fds: Mean +- std dev: 117 ms +- 2 msn.....................nspawn native close_fds: Mean +- std dev: 1.36 ms +- 0.03 msn.....................nspawn gevent close_fds: Mean +- std dev: 32.5 ms +- 0.4 msnnNotice that gevent is *much* slower when we *don't* close the fds.nThis is because, starting in Python 3.4, close_fds defaults to true,nand when it's false we have to check os.get_inheritable() for each fdnbefore we close it. gevent performs the same as it did on Python 2.7nwhen closing fds, but the native implementation is much faster due tonthe C optimizations outlined in #1172---it turns out they apply to BSDnand Apple platforms in addition to Linux, although they're not asyncnsafe.nnNow, the C code does the opposite for inheritable handles: itnexplicitly calls make_inheritable() for the ones it wants to keep andnlets the OS close the others with CLOEXEC. We could probably do thatntoo; the slow down for this case counts as a regression, I think.n

Use /dev/fd|/proc/self/fd to get open FDs to close in PopenIf those aren't available, use the old brute-force approach. This isncloser to what CPython does in its C implementation, and is muchnfaster.nnWe don't have to worry about the async signal safe stuff the C codendoes because, guess what, we're running Python code here alreadynanyway, so much of it could wind up doing something that's notnactually safe anyway. Oh well.nnSince we depend on Python 3.4 and above now, we can rely on thenCLOEXEC flag being set by default and not have to manually checkneverything.nnThis speeds up 2.7 (close_fds defaults to *false* there, so thendefault case doesn't change):nn| Benchmark | 27_bench_subprocess | 27_bench_subprocess_dirfd |n+---------------------------+---------------------+-------------------------------+n| spawn native no close_fds | 1.81 ms | 1.79 ms: 1.01x faster (-1%)   |n| spawn gevent no close_fds | 2.11 ms | 2.20 ms: 1.04x slower (+4%)   |n| spawn native close_fds| 31.0 ms | 30.2 ms: 1.03x faster (-3%)   |n| spawn gevent close_fds| 31.6 ms | 2.56 ms: 12.31x faster (-92%) |nnAnd it really speeds up 3.7 (close_fds defaults to *true* there, sonthe default case is much faster, and the non-default case is even better):nn| Benchmark | 37_bench_subprocess | 37_bench_subprocess_dirfd |n+---------------------------+---------------------+-------------------------------+n| spawn native no close_fds | 1.34 ms | 1.27 ms: 1.06x faster (-6%)   |n| spawn gevent no close_fds | 117 ms  | 3.05 ms: 38.27x faster (-97%) |n| spawn native close_fds| 1.36 ms | 1.30 ms: 1.04x faster (-4%)   |n| spawn gevent close_fds| 32.5 ms | 3.34 ms: 9.75x faster (-90%)  |nnFixes #1172n

Make Semaphores fair.Preserve order of wakeups. Take steps to avoid going back to the O(n^2) old behaviour, though, much like Greenlet does.nnThis means we auto-unlink links as we call them. Most users won't notice as that's a very low-level method, but baseserver.py was relying on the same rawlink being called every time a semaphore became ready. That was *a lot*, so this eliminates some calls.n

Fix an interaction between the switch interval and libuv that could introduce delays processing large batches of callbacks.Specifically, a .3 (idle signal timer) delay as UV_RUN_ONCE would pause if there was no other active timer or IO watcher.nnNow, if there are still batches of callbacks to run, we explicitly use UV_RUN_NOWAIT to only poll for IO and queue callbacks without waiting at all.nnThis gets the time for the synthetic greenlet-launching benchmarks to match libev-cffi and be close to libuv-cext.nnFixes #1493n
